 style=3D"Margin:0 0
24px 0;"><em>What you need to know today about the chaos at Macy=E2=80=99s<=
/em>: I worked at Macy=E2=80=99s Inc. for more than a decade as a buyer for=
 Bloomingdale=E2=80=99s, where I also developed the private label merchandi=
se that was supposed to drive margin, but often ended up in the remainder b=
in. So I had a <em>very</em> proximate view of the multidecade decline of M=
acy=E2=80=99s, itself, which was first threatened by the rise of specialty =
retail in the early =E2=80=9980s and then big box stores (Walmart, Target, =
etcetera) in
the =E2=80=9990s, before Amazon even entered the picture and obviated much =
of the need for its 700 remaining stores=E2=80=94still a staggering number.=
<div>=C2=A0</div>The group delayed the reporting of its third-quarter resul=
ts because a now-fired employee apparently somehow hid about <em>$150 milli=
on</em> in delivery expenses over the course of a few years. Unsurprisingly=
, my group chats were on fire when the company announced this news, with ex=
-employees not only appalled, but also shocked that this sort of
<em>accounting nit </em>went unnoticed by the notoriously frugal, penny-pin=
ching bean counters. When I worked at the group, I=E2=80=99d hear from the =
finance department if a vendor was even a few days late on a $25 <em>charge=
-back</em>=E2=80=94the money a brand has to pay a retailer if their product=
 doesn=E2=80=99t sell for full price. (I=E2=80=99m not exaggerating.) So I=
=E2=80=99m still not sure how KPMG, Macy=E2=80=99s accounting firm since th=
e =E2=80=9980s, missed <em>$150 million</em>, even if it=E2=80=99s out of $=
4 billion in delivery expenses.<div>=C2=A0
</div>Anyway, the bigger problem for Macy=E2=80=99s is its continual descen=
t in the ever-shrinking middle market. The <em>real</em> red flag in the ea=
rnings report was the fact that the company=E2=80=99s e-commerce revenue <e=
m>declined</em> while the sector is growing rapidly. Meanwhile, activist in=
vestors Barington Capital, the guys who were behind the spinoff of Bath &am=
p; Body Works from Victoria=E2=80=99s Secret, and Thor Equities are trying =
to carve out the good and bad assets. (The good: Bloomingdale=E2=80=99s, Se=
phora
competitor Blue Mercury, and of course, the real estate portfolio=E2=80=94i=
ncluding the Herald Square flagship, which is well-positioned amid the broa=
der financial investment east of Hudson Yards. The bad: almost everything e=
lse=E2=80=A6)<div>=C2=A0</div>While the company rejected a $5.8 billion tak=
e-private offer at the beginning of this year, activists could push another=
 deal. In the meantime, Macy=E2=80=99s needs to turn around its e-commerce =
business and reignite poorly performing stores. (Sixty-five locations are
scheduled to close after the holidays. By 2026, that number is expected to =
climb to 150, or 30 percent of the company=E2=80=99s current retail footpri=
nt.) Right now, sales at most stores aren=E2=80=99t growing. The company br=
eaks out sales for the 50 top-performing stores, which grew 1.9 percent dur=
ing the last quarter. That=E2=80=99s concerning, given that these are suppo=
sed to be the most productive locations.<div>=C2=A0</div>The good news is t=
hat still-newish group C.E.O. <strong>Tony Spring</strong> is a company
lifer who had decades of success preserving and slowly pivoting Bloomingdal=
e=E2=80=99s to survive in the hybrid marketplace. You have to wonder though=
, after this Saks-Neiman Marcus deal goes through, will HBC chairman <stron=
g>Richard Baker</strong> come a-calling? I jumped on the phone with BMO ana=
lyst<strong> Simeon Siegel </strong>the other day to work out some theories=
 regarding what happens next. The most likely scenario is that Bloomingdale=
=E2=80=99s and Blue Mercury are sold off and the money from the
sale is reinvested to fix Macy=E2=80=99s, but I don=E2=80=99t think we=E2=
=80=99re there yet. (Alas, Macy=E2=80=99s doesn=E2=80=99t own the flagship =
Bloomingdale=E2=80=99s building on 59th and Lex, which is part of the <stro=
ng>Joseph</strong> and <strong>Lyman</strong> <strong>Bloomingdale</strong>=
 family trust.) If you know anything, or simply want to chat about the eter=
nal existential crisis facing department stores, hit me up at <a href=3D"ma=
ilto:sshapiro@puck.news?utm_campaign=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F19%=
2F24%29&amp;utm_content=3DLine+Sheet+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2812%2F19%2F24%29&amp;u=
tm_medium=3Demail_action&amp;utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&amp;utm_term=3Df6c606=
17da42abd12a" style=3D"text-decoration:underline;color:#d40000;"><strong>SS=
hapiro@puck.news</strong></a>.
</li><li style=3D"Margin:0 0 24px 0;"><em>Does a designer=E2=80=99s exit re=
ally impact a brand=E2=80=99s topline at retail?</em>: On resale sites, sup=
ply and demand can very much influence the =E2=80=9Cvalue=E2=80=9D of items=
 and drive price points and interest up. Last week, after <strong>Louise Tr=
otter</strong> exited Carven for Bottega Veneta, and it was announced that =
